The issue you are facing is that you are trying to access the TextView object outside of the method where it is declared. When you declare a variable inside a method, it is only accessible within that method. To fix this issue, you should declare the TextView object as a class variable and then instantiate it inside each method where it is needed.

Here's an example of how you can declare the TextView object as a class variable and instantiate it inside each method:
```java
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    private TextView tv_scoreDisplay;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        // Instantiate the TextView object
        tv_scoreDisplay = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.tv_scoreDisplay);

        // Use the TextView object in this method
        updateScore();
    }

    private void updateScore() {
        // Use the TextView object in this method
        tv_scoreDisplay.setText("Score: " + getScore());
    }

    private int getScore() {
        // Code to get the score
        return 10;
    }
}
```
In this example, the TextView object is declared as a class variable `tv_scoreDisplay` in the `MainActivity` class. It is then instantiated inside the `onCreate()` method using the `findViewById()` method. Finally, it is used in the `updateScore()` method to update the score displayed on the screen.

By declaring the TextView object as a class variable and instantiating it inside each method where it is needed, you can avoid the NullPointerException error you were encountering.
